<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911220-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>911220-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Safety-Kleen Corp.:   Quarter's Per-Share Earnings   Are Expected to Fall 35%</HL><DATE>12/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SK WNEWS</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Safety-Kleen Corp., Elgin, Ill., said fourth-quarterper-share earnings are expected to fall about 35% to 24 centsa share from 37 cents a share a year ago.   The car and industrial equipment concern said per-shareearnings for the year are expected to be about 90 cents ashare, down from $1.05 a share.</LP><TEXT>   Safety-Kleen said the quarter will reflect a net charge of$1.2 million related to the previously announced settlementof an action brought by California in April, allegingviolations of the state's Hazardous Waste Act. The companyalso will take a charge of $800,000 to write off costs froman attempt to get a permit to construct a solvent recyclingplant in North Las Vegas, Nev.   The company said that even without the two charges,fourth-quarter earnings would have been down 18% to 20% on a17% increase in revenue.   Separately, Safety-Kleen said its chairman and chiefexecutive officer, Donald W. Brinckman, was named to theadditional post of president. Mr. Brinckman succeeds JosephF. Knott, who died Dec. 2.   In New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday, Safety-Kleenfell $1 to $23.75.</TEXT></DOC>